To complain about the smoldering Arab that came crashing through his ceiling!! BOOM!!!


Don’t care if it’s too soon. It’s also too good.

@Cekseiro I didn't say it wouldn't be over FASTER than doing nothing. Nor did I say anything about sympathy, or anything even remotely close. Nor am I even actually accusing the US for loving oil "too much" (its just what they do, so its a potential reasoning)

I'm just saying; Wars not over. Everyone who CAN stop war from continuing, likely won't. Benefits, revenge, etc etc. 

Its not over in 24 hrs. Its not even going to be over "soon". Though tbf soon also depends on someone's definition of soon.

@PuchimonExtreme I said I didn't sympathize with the arguments raised in the response an hour or so ago (though I also suspect I slightly misread it, on re-read), not accusing you of sympathy towards the regime. I apologize if I gave the wrong impression on that, not always the best at picking my words.


Either way, I do agree with the sentiment that it's not over until the fat lady sings, and that it has the potential to get even uglier both in the immediate short-term and in the aftermath regardless of how cautious we are about it--though I firmly believe that this is significantly better than just allowing them to continue on, in part because of how many of my countrymen the clerics have caused the deaths of and would continue to cause the deaths of in the future. At least this way, the funding eventually dries up.


As for the oil thing, part of why I latched onto it is because I'm used to people dismissing every single action that the US does in the region as being because of oil. Though really, oil probably does factor in a bit... though, not how you'd expect. Rather, instead of this particular motivation being based on us getting oil, it'd be on ensuring China and Russia do not, reducing their capacity to wage war at-scale. Which means China won't be able to risk moving on Taiwan and Russia's capacity to sustain its own ongoing efforts is going to get a bit thinner, while hitting them both in the economy through the increased gas prices. Which is good for the rest of the world because the less likely either of them are to try to start something, the less likely WW3 pops off.
